h (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the places in Calvados and Orne, France, named Corbon.","Irish: variant of   Corban  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carbin","meanings":["Swedish: soldier's name, from Swedish <i>karbin</i> ‘carbine’, a type of short rifle or musket used by cavalry.","Cornish: hypercorrect backformation from Cornish <i>carr-bons</i> ‘causeway’, or a habitational name from Carbis in Lelant (Cornwall), of the same derivation.","English: variant of   Corbin  ."]},{"name":"Corvin","meanings":["English (Durham): possibly a variant of   Corbin  .","Altered form of Scottish, Irish or English   Colvin  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Korving</b> (mainly The Hague): from the personal name <i>Korving</i>, from <i>Corvinus</i>, from Latin <i>corvus</i> ‘raven’."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Corbin was born about 1380, in Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England, his father, Henry Corbin, was 22 and his mother, Margery Day, was 22. He married Elizabeth Margery Blount about 1398. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1430, in Staffordshire, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1380–about 1430":"umbes 1380–umbes 1430","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1398–1414":"1398–1414","1380–1470":"1380–1470","1398–1460":"1398–1460","1415–1477":"1415–1477","1418–Male":"1418–Surnud","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1477":"1477","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","about 1398":"umbes 1398","1418":"1418","about 1430":"umbes 1430","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, England","Corbyn Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1380–about 1430":"noin 1380–noin 1430","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1398–1414":"1398–1414","1380–1470":"1380–1470","1398–1460":"1398–1460","1415–1477":"1415–1477","1418–Male":"1418–Kuollut","1360–1430":"1360–1430","1360–Female":"1360–Kuoll